Cape Town - South African lifesavers were victorious at the recently completed African Lifesaving Championship in Alexandria, Egypt, taking first place in the competition.The South African team beat 17 other countries, ending the competition with 500 points, ahead of hosts Egypt in second place (468 points) and Morocco in third place (410 points).There were nine events in the competition – eight men’s and women’s races in the same categories and one mixed relay race.The Egyptian Diving and Lifesaving Federation (ELDF) sponsored accommodation and meals for the athletes during their stay at the competition.The South African team comprised of lifesavers from all over the country, predominantly KZN and the Western Cape. Some of the standout results include Travis Misdorp (Marine Lifesaving Club), who won the gold medal in-board race; Kristin Bellingan (Marine Lifesaving Club) taking home gold; Tatum Botha (uMhlanga Rocks Lifesaving Club) winning silver in the ladies’ board; and the mixed beach sprint relay team winning gold. The team secured a host of other second and third-place finishes in what was a dominant showing all round.Dr Mohamed Ali Gharbal, president of the International Lifesaving Federation (ILS) – Africa Confederation, said: “The African Championship was masterfully organised by the Egyptian Diving and Lifesaving Federation and has not only shone a light on lifesaving sport in Egypt, but will also accentuate the youthful energy and high performance that all lifesaving sport disciplines can bring to Africa and the world stage.”His sentiments were echoed by Sameh El-Shazly, president of the EDLF.“I am delighted to have welcomed all the joining teams who represent different African nations in a fair competition that has resulted in growing up and empowering the friendship between all participants.”matthew.petersen@inl.co.zaCape Argus